Three years into building an enterprise dashboard for a logistics company, our lead engineer pulled me into a call at 11 PM. Client was furious. The app took nine seconds to load a table with four hundred rows. Nine seconds. In a warehouse where dispatchers needed real time data, nine seconds felt like an hour.
I opened Chrome DevTools that night expecting a network problem.
It was not the network. It was us.
Every single row in that table was running through Angular’s default change detection, checking every binding, every pipe, every ngIf, on every tick, whether anything changed or not. We had built a slow machine and blamed the internet for it.
That night changed how I write Angular code forever.
What follows are the twenty techniques that took that same dashboard from a nine second load to under two seconds, with real numbers, real code, and no filler. Grab a coffee. This one is worth the read.

Why Most Angular Apps Are Slower Than They Should Be
Angular gives you enormous power out of the box. That power comes with defaults that are safe, not fast.
Here is the architecture problem in a simple diagram, drawn the old fashioned way:
Default Angular Change Detection
---------------------------------Root Component
|
|---> checks EVERY child, EVERY tick
| |
| |---> Component A (unchanged) -- still checked
| |---> Component B (unchanged) -- still checked
| |---> Component C (changed) -- checked
|
+---> repeats on every event, timer, HTTP responseCompare that to the optimized version:
OnPush + Signals Change Detection
-----------------------------------Root Component
|
|---> Component A (unchanged) -- SKIPPED
|---> Component B (unchanged) -- SKIPPED
|---> Component C (changed) -- checked onlyThat single shift, from checking everything to checking only what changed, is where most of your performance is hiding. Let us walk through it, technique by technique.

1. Switch to OnPush Change Detection
This is the single highest leverage change you can make in an existing app.
@Component({
selector: 'app-order-row',
changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
template: `<td>{{ order.id }}</td><td>{{ order.status }}</td>`
})
export class OrderRowComponent {
@Input() order!: Order;
}The problem: Angular was re-checking every row component on every browser event, even a mouse move.
The change: Added ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush so the component only re-renders when its input reference changes.
The result: On our 400 row table, change detection cycles dropped from 1,800ms to 240ms per full refresh, measured with the Angular DevTools profiler.

2. Add trackBy to Every ngFor
trackByOrderId(index: number, order: Order) {
return order.id;
}<tr *ngFor="let order of orders; trackBy: trackByOrderId">The problem: Without trackBy, Angular destroys and rebuilds every DOM node in a list whenever the array reference changes, even if only one item was updated.
The change: Added an identity function so Angular can match old items to new ones.
The result: Re-rendering 400 rows after a single field update dropped from 620ms to 40ms.

3. Lazy Load Every Feature Route
const routes: Routes = [
{
path: 'reports',
loadComponent: () => import('./reports/reports.component')
.then(m => m.ReportsComponent)
}
];The problem: Our initial bundle was 2.4MB because every module loaded on first paint, including admin panels most users never touched.
The change: Converted every feature area to lazy loaded standalone routes.
The result: Initial bundle dropped to 480KB. Time to Interactive improved from 6.1s to 2.3s on a throttled 4G connection.

4. Use Virtual Scrolling for Long Lists
import { ScrollingModule } from '@angular/cdk/scrolling';<cdk-virtual-scroll-viewport itemSize="48" class="viewport">
<div *cdkVirtualFor="let order of orders">{{ order.id }}</div>
</cdk-virtual-scroll-viewport>The problem: Rendering all 400 rows to the DOM at once, even off screen ones, was consuming memory and slowing scroll performance.
The change: Replaced the plain ngFor table with CDK virtual scrolling, which only renders visible rows.
The result: DOM nodes dropped from 3,200 to roughly 60 at any given time. Scroll jank disappeared completely on mid range laptops.

5. Move to Signals for State That Changes Often
count = signal(0);
doubled = computed(() => this.count() * 2);increment() {
this.count.update(v => v + 1);
}The problem: RxJS BehaviorSubjects combined with the async pipe were triggering full subtree checks even for isolated counter updates.
The change: Replaced high frequency state with signals, which notify Angular precisely which components depend on them.
The result: Fine grained updates meant a single counter change no longer triggered a check across the entire dashboard.

6. Avoid Function Calls Inside Templates
// Bad
<div>{{ calculateTotal(order) }}</div>// Good
<div>{{ order.total }}</div>The problem: A method in a template runs on every single change detection cycle, not just when data changes.
The change: Precomputed values in the component class or used a pure pipe instead.
The result: Removed roughly 400 unnecessary function executions per second during active scrolling, verified through the Performance tab.

7. Use Pure Pipes Instead of Methods
@Pipe({ name: 'currencyFmt', pure: true, standalone: true })
export class CurrencyFmtPipe implements PipeTransform {
transform(value: number): string {
return `$${value.toFixed(2)}`;
}
}The problem: Formatting logic written as a component method re-ran on every tick.
The change: Moved formatting into a pure pipe, which only recalculates when its input actually changes.
The result: CPU time spent on formatting dropped by roughly 80% during rapid state updates.

8. Detach Change Detection for Static Widgets
constructor(private cdRef: ChangeDetectorRef) {
this.cdRef.detach();
}refreshManually() {
this.cdRef.detectChanges();
}The problem: A sidebar widget showing static company branding was still being checked hundreds of times a minute.
The change: Detached it from the change detection tree entirely and refreshed it manually only when needed.
The result: Removed an entire subtree from every check cycle at zero visual cost.

9. Run Heavy Work Outside Angular’s Zone
constructor(private ngZone: NgZone) {}startPolling() {
this.ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
setInterval(() => this.fetchLiveData(), 3000);
});
}The problem: A live data poller was triggering a full change detection cycle every three seconds across the whole app, not just the widget using the data.
The change: Ran the interval outside Angular’s zone and manually re-entered the zone only to update the relevant component.
The result: Background polling stopped affecting unrelated parts of the UI, cutting idle CPU usage by close to a third.

10. Use the New @defer Block for Below the Fold Content
@defer (on viewport) {
<app-analytics-chart />
} @placeholder {
<div class="skeleton"></div>
}The problem: A heavy charting library was loading on first paint even though the chart lived below the fold.
The change: Wrapped it in a defer block that loads only when it enters the viewport.
The result: First Contentful Paint improved by 1.4 seconds without touching the chart code itself.

11. Unsubscribe Properly with takeUntilDestroyed
private destroyRef = inject(DestroyRef);ngOnInit() {
this.orderService.orders$
.pipe(takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef))
.subscribe(orders => this.orders = orders);
}The problem: Old subscriptions were piling up as users navigated between pages, quietly leaking memory.
The change: Adopted takeUntilDestroyed across every subscription in the codebase.
The result: Memory usage during a 20 minute user session dropped from 340MB to 190MB, measured in the Chrome Memory tab.

12. Debounce User Input Before Triggering Requests
this.searchControl.valueChanges.pipe(
debounceTime(300),
distinctUntilChanged(),
takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef)
).subscribe(term => this.search(term));The problem: A search box was firing an HTTP request on every keystroke.
The change: Added debounce and distinctUntilChanged to the input stream.
The result: Requests per search session dropped from an average of 14 to 3, reducing both server load and UI flicker.

13. Use NgOptimizedImage for Every Image
<img ngSrc="dashboard-hero.webp" width="800" height="400" priority>The problem: Unoptimized hero images were blocking the largest contentful paint on the landing dashboard.
The change: Switched every static image to the NgOptimizedImage directive with explicit dimensions.
The result: Largest Contentful Paint improved from 3.8s to 1.6s on mobile devices.

14. Set Bundle Budgets and Actually Respect Them
"budgets": [
{
"type": "initial",
"maximumWarning": "500kb",
"maximumError": "800kb"
}
]The problem: Bundle size crept up silently over eighteen months as new libraries were added without review.
The change: Set hard budgets in angular.json that fail the build if exceeded.
The result: Forced the team to catch three unnecessary heavy dependencies before they ever reached production.

15. Analyze and Trim Your Bundle Regularly
ng build --stats-json
npx webpack-bundle-analyzer dist/stats.jsonThe problem: We assumed our bundle was lean. It was not. A date library we used for one formatting call was adding 180KB alone.
The change: Ran the bundle analyzer monthly and replaced heavy libraries with lightweight alternatives or native APIs.
The result: Total bundle size dropped by 22% in a single sprint with zero feature changes.

16. Cache HTTP Responses That Do Not Change Often
private cache = new Map<string, Observable<any>>();getReferenceData(key: string) {
if (!this.cache.has(key)) {
this.cache.set(key, this.http.get(`/api/ref/${key}`).pipe(shareReplay(1)));
}
return this.cache.get(key)!;
}The problem: Dropdown reference data was being fetched fresh every time a user opened a form, even though it changed once a week.
The change: Added an in memory cache with shareReplay for reference endpoints.
The result: Reduced redundant API calls by roughly 90% across a typical user session.

17. Preload Strategically, Not Everything
RouterModule.forRoot(routes, {
preloadingStrategy: PreloadAllModules
})Better, use a custom strategy:
export class SelectivePreload implements PreloadingStrategy {
preload(route: Route, load: () => Observable<any>) {
return route.data?.['preload'] ? load() : of(null);
}
}The problem: Preloading every module defeated the purpose of lazy loading in the first place.
The change: Built a custom strategy that only preloads routes marked as high priority in route data.
The result: Kept the fast initial load while still making the two most visited routes feel instant on navigation.

18. Use Server Side Rendering with Hydration
bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, {
providers: [provideClientHydration()]
});The problem: Our public facing pages had poor First Contentful Paint because the browser had to download, parse, and execute JavaScript before showing anything.
The change: Enabled Angular Universal with client hydration for public routes.
The result: First Contentful Paint on those pages improved from 2.9s to 0.9s, and it helped organic search rankings within weeks.

19. Move Expensive Computation to a Web Worker
const worker = new Worker(new URL('./report.worker', import.meta.url));
worker.postMessage(rawData);
worker.onmessage = ({ data }) => this.processedReport = data;The problem: Generating a complex report from 10,000 rows froze the entire UI thread for nearly two seconds.
The change: Moved the calculation into a dedicated web worker so it runs off the main thread.
The result: The UI stayed fully responsive during report generation, with zero frame drops recorded during the operation.

20. Measure Everything Before You Optimize Anything
ng build --configuration production --source-map
npx source-map-explorer dist/main.jsThe problem: Early in the project, we optimized components nobody actually used heavily, wasting two full days.
